04941nam a22006975i 9781782048268DE-B159720240306014423.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20162016xxk    fo  d z      eng d  a97817820482687 a10.1515/97817820482682doi  a(DE-B1597)674150  a(OCoLC)1419790562  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxkcUK 4aPR6060.E55 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a823/.914qLOC2231 aMundler, Helen E., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Otherworlds of Liz Jensen :bA Critical Reading /cHelen E. Mundler.31aWoodbridge, Suffolk : bBoydell and Brewer, c[2016] 1bCamden House, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (244 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStudies in English and American Literature and Culture ;v2500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction -- t1: Egg Dancing: Paving the Way for Otherworlds in Time and Space -- t2: Ark Baby and the Return to the Nineteenth Century -- t3: Island Life: The Pure “Ustopia” of The Paper Eater -- t4: Liz Jensen’s Murder Mysteries -- t5: From Family Romance to the Detective Novel -- t6: New Rules, New Otherworlds: Jensen’s “Third Wave” -- t7: Ecofiction, Rapture Fiction -- t8: The Uninvited: The Most Radically “Other” World to Date -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe first study of one of the most innovative of contemporary novelists, Liz Jensen, and of the "otherworlds" in her fiction.Liz Jensen, a British author of eight novels, is among today's most innovative writers. Her literary thrillers occupy the terrain between realism and science fiction. This first study of Jensen centers on the very diverse "otherworlds" she creates in each of her novels, which can consist of an indeterminate space of ontological instability, a zone in which real and unreal converge to destabilize the realist text, as in Egg Dancing (1995) and TheNinth Life of Louis Drax (2004). In other novels the otherworld relies on defamiliarization: thus in War Crimes for the Home (2002) the experience of war is transformed by being seen from a woman's perspective. In stillother cases, the otherworld spans the novel's entire topos, as in The Paper Eater (2000), the full-blown utopia at the center of Jensen's oeuvre. Jensen's work approaches contemporary social issues such as religious fundamentalism, ecological disaster, and assisted procreation. Simultaneously, it displays a number of characteristics of erudite fiction, including self-reflexivity, inter- and intratextual reference, parody, pastiche, and burlesque. Notwithstanding the "popular" elements of Jensen's work, Helen E. Mundler's study adopts a rigorously academic approach to it, referencing canonical works but also more innovative texts, particularly by contemporary women writers, as points of comparison. Helen E. Mundler is Senior Lecturer in English Studies at UPEC (Université Paris-Est Créteil) with a research affiliation at the Université Paris-X Nanterre-La Défense.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aFantastic, The, in literature. 0aLiterature and society. 0aReality in literature. 0aSociety in literature. 0aSurprise in literature. 4aEnglish & American Literature. 4aWomen's & Gender Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  aBritish thrillers.  aEnglish literature.  acontemporary British fiction.  afeminist authors.  aliterary analysis.  amodern British literature.  amodern women writers.  asci-fi.  atwenty-first century British literature.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311143131440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/